# Conditional Statements

Conditional statements allow your program to make decisions and execute different blocks of code based on whether a condition is true or false.

---

## 1. The if Statement
The most basic form of decision-making.

```cpp
if (condition) {
    // Code to execute if condition is true
}
```

## 2. The if-else Statement
Provides an alternative if the condition is false.

```cpp
if (age >= 18) {
    std::cout << "Adult";
} else {
    std::cout << "Minor";
}
```

## 3. The else-if Ladder
Used to check multiple conditions sequentially.

## 4. The switch Statement
A more efficient way to check a single variable against multiple constant values.

```cpp
switch (choice) {
    case 1: std::cout << "Option 1"; break;
    case 2: std::cout << "Option 2"; break;
    default: std::cout << "Invalid";
}
```

**Note**: Always use `break` in a switch case to prevent "falling through" to the next case.

