# Arrays in C++

An array is a collection of elements of the **same data type** stored at contiguous memory locations.

---

## 1. One-Dimensional (1D) Arrays

```cpp
int numbers[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
```
- **Indexing**: Arrays start at index **0**.
- **Accessing**: `numbers[0]` is 10, `numbers[4]` is 50.

## 2. Two-Dimensional (2D) Arrays
Commonly used for grids and matrices.

```cpp
int matrix[2][3] = {
    {1, 2, 3},
    {4, 5, 6}
};
```

## 3. Passing Arrays to Functions
Arrays are passed by **reference** (pointer to the first element) by default.

```cpp
void printArray(int arr[], int size) {
    for(int i = 0; i < size; i++) std::cout << arr[i];
}
```

lessons.fullProgram:
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    int scores[3] = {85, 92, 78};

    std::cout << "Scores: ";
    for(int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
        std::cout << scores[i] << " ";
    }

    int matrix[2][2] = {{1, 2}, {3, 4}};
    std::cout << "\nMatrix element [1][0]: " << matrix[1][0];

    return 0;
}

#include <iostream>

int main() {
    int age = 25;
    int* pAge = &age;

    std::cout << "Value of age: " << age << "\n";
    std::cout << "Address of age (&age): " << &age << "\n";
    std::cout << "Value through pointer (*pAge): " << *pAge << "\n";

    *pAge = 30; // Modify age using pointer
    std::cout << "New age: " << age;

    return 0;
}

