# Classes & Objects

Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a paradigm that uses **Objects** to represent real-world entities. A **Class** is a blueprint for an object.

---

## 1. Class Structure

```cpp
class Student {
public:
    string name;  // Attribute
    int age;     // Attribute

    void display() { // Method
        cout << name << " " << age;
    }
};
```

## 2. Access Specifiers
- **public**: Members are accessible from outside the class.
- **private**: Members are ONLY accessible within the class.
- **protected**: Members are accessible in the class and its inherited classes.

## 3. Constructors & Destructors
- **Constructor**: A special method called automatically when an object is created. Usually used for initialization.
- **Destructor**: Called when an object is destroyed. Starts with `~`.

```cpp
class Car {
public:
    Car() { cout << "Car created!"; }  // Constructor
    ~Car() { cout << "Car destroyed!"; } // Destructor
};
```

lessons.fullProgram:
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

class Dog {
public:
    std::string breed;

    // Constructor
    Dog(std::string b) {
        breed = b;
    }

    void bark() {
        std::cout << breed << " says: Woof!\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Dog myDog("Golden Retriever");
    myDog.bark();
    return 0;
}

#include <iostream>

class Shape {
public:
    virtual void draw() {
        std::cout << "Drawing a generic shape...\n";
    }
};

class Circle : public Shape {
public:
    void draw() override {
        std::cout << "Drawing a Circle!\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Shape* s = new Circle();
    s->draw(); // Calls Circle's draw() due to polymorphism
    delete s;
    return 0;
}

#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> nums = {5, 2, 8, 1, 9};

    // Using STL Algorithm to sort
    std::sort(nums.begin(), nums.end());

    std::cout << "Sorted Vector: ";
    for(int n : nums) {
        std::cout << n << " ";
    }

    return 0;
}

